{{Infobox Athletics Championships |Name = Athletics at the XI Bolivarian Games |Logo = |Size = 200px |Colour = #FAAC58 |Optional caption = |Host city = [[Maracaibo]], [[Venezuela]] {{flagicon|Venezuela}} |Dates = January 14–25
|Stadium = [[Estadio José Pachencho Romero]] |Nations participating = |Athletes participating = |Events = 40 (23 men, 17 women) |Records set = |Level = Senior |Previous = [[Athletics at the 1985 Bolivarian Games|1985 Cuenca]] |Next = [[Athletics at the 1993 Bolivarian Games|1993 Cochabamba]] |Games = [[1989 Bolivarian Games]] }}
'''[[Athletics (sport)|Athletics]]''' competitions at the '''[[1989 Bolivarian Games]]''' were held at the [[Estadio José Pachencho Romero]] in [[Maracaibo]], [[Venezuela]], between January 14–25, 1989.
A detailed history of the early editions of the Bolivarian Games between 1938 and 1989 was published in a book written (in Spanish) by José Gamarra Zorrilla, former president of the Bolivian Olympic Committee, and first president (1976-1982) of [[ODESUR]].<ref name=bolivia> {{ Citation | last = Gamarra Zorrilla | first = José | date = | title = Bolivia Olímpica Capítulos VI al VIII | url = http://www.andesacd.org/wp-content/uploads/2012/01/Bolivia-Ol%C3%ADmpica-Cap%C3%ADtulos-VI-al-VIII.pdf | publisher = ANDES Academia del Conocimiento y el Desarrollo "Fernando Diez de Medina" | language = Spanish | accessdate = June 28, 2012 }} </ref> Gold medal winners from Ecuador were published by the Comité Olímpico Ecuatoriano.<ref> {{ Citation |last= |first= |date= |title=CUADRO DE MEDALLISTAS ECUATORIANOS EN LA HISTORIA DE LOS J. D. B. POR EDICIÓN |url=http://www.coe.org.ec/pdf/Medallas_Ecuador/JUEGOS_BOLIVARIANOS_1938-1997.pdf |publisher=Comité Olímpico Ecuatoriano |language=Spanish |accessdate=June 28, 2012 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120608185327/http://www.coe.org.ec/pdf/Medallas_Ecuador/JUEGOS_BOLIVARIANOS_1938-1997.pdf |archivedate=June 8, 2012 |df= }} </ref>
A total of 40 events were contested, 23 by men and 17 by women.
