{{italic title}} '''''Procession at Seville and bullfighting Scenes''''' is a [[non-fiction]] [[short film]] created by [[Auguste and Louis Lumière]] between 1898 and 1899.<ref name="El País">{{cite news|last1=Constenla|first1=Tereixa|title=Los incunables que España perdió|url=http://elpais.com/diario/2009/04/26/cultura/1240696802_850215.html|accessdate=3 November 2016|work=El País|agency=El País|issue=1|publisher=PRISA|date=2009-04-26|ref=El País}}</ref> <ref name="Arte Sacro">{{cite web|last1=Arte Sacro|first1=Arte Sacro|title=Video de la Hermandad de la Estrella con su Centuria y Escenas de Corridas de Toros|url=http://www.artesacro.org/Noticia.asp?idreg=48832#|website=Arte Sacro|publisher=Arte Sacro|accessdate=3 November 2016|ref=Arte Sacro}}</ref> The Lumière brothers used a [[cinematograph]] to film this motion picture in [[Seville]], Spain.<ref name="Sevilla Ciudad de Cine Encadenados">{{cite journal|last1=Pablos Pons|first1=Juan|title=Sevilla, ciudad de cine|journal=Encadenados|date=2014-10-21|volume=86|issue=Rashomon|page=17|url=http://www.encadenados.org/rdc/rashomon/129-rashomon-n-86-ciudades-de-pelicula/3788-sevilla-ciudad-de-cine|accessdate=1 November 2016}}</ref>
==Plot==
''Procession at Seville and bullfighting scenes'' depicts the traditional Spanish [[Holy Week]] celebration, portraying Spain in the 19th century. This recording includes a traditional parade and [[Bullfighting|bullfights]] in Spain, representing how this holiday was celebrated at the time.<ref name="Arte Sacro" /> At the beginning, the short film shows the Procession Parade from the Christ of Sorrows. This celebration occurs during [[Holy Week in Seville]] which is celebrated one week before Easter. It includes decorated chariots that are pulled around the city streets by ''Costaleros''. The ''Penitentes'', dressed in tunics and a cape, march together in the procession along with the chariots and other people wearing traditional and formal clothing <ref name="WDL">{{cite journal|last1=Société Anonyme des Plaques et Papiers Photographiques Antoine Lumière|first1=Société Lumière|title=Descargas Procesión en Sevilla y escenas de corridas de toros|journal=World Digital Library|date=12/02/ 2016|volume=1|issue=1|page=2|url=https://www.wdl.org/es/item/536/#featured_item=true&page=2|accessdate=3 November 2016|ref=Société Lumière}}</ref> During the bullfighting celebration, the ''Banderillero'' entertains the bull and plays with it, meanwhile a ''[[Picador]]'' (Lancer) enters the spectacle. The Picador is riding a horse and manages to stab the bull. The short film displays the process of bullfighting and how each participant plays their specific role, as well as the traditional parade.<ref name="El Correo">{{cite web|last1=El Correo de Andalucía|first1=El Correo|title=Sevilla, vista por los hermanos Lumière|url=http://elcorreoweb.es/historico/sevilla-vista-por-los-hermanos-lumiere-MBEC169137|website=El Correo Web|publisher=El Correo|accessdate=3 November 2016|ref=El Correo Web de Andalucía}}</ref>
==Production and development==
===Production===
To create the short film, the Lumière Brothers used a [[cinematograph]], a new projection device which was beginning to be used at that time.<ref name="El Correo" /> The brothers sent different equipment all over the world in order to film a variety of scenes and images. Two of the main filming locations were France and Spain.<ref name="El Correo" /> This short [[non-fiction]] film marked the first time that someone filmed the Spanish Holy Week.<ref name="Aciprensa">{{cite web|last1=Ruiz|first1=Bianca|title=Hermanos Lumière, padres del cine moderno, pioneros en grabar Semana Santa de Sevilla|url=https://www.aciprensa.com/noticias/hermanos-lumiere-padres-del-cine-moderno-pioneros-en-grabar-semana-santa-de-sevilla-36981/|website=Aciprensa|publisher=EWTN Noticias|accessdate=3 November 2016|ref=Aciprensa}}</ref>
==Distribution and reception==
The first 1,000 copies of this film were distributed by Auguste and Louis Lumière. ''Procession at Seville and bullfighting scenes'' was found later on a 16mm reel and a videocassette, along with other 46 Lumière films.<ref name="WolrdCat">{{cite web|first1=La Société Lumière|title=Procession at Séville and bullfighting scenes|url=http://www.worldcat.org/title/procession-at-seville-and-bullfighting-scenes/oclc/76783352|website=WorldCat|publisher=Online Computer Library Center|accessdate=1 November 2016}}</ref> After this, the [[Library of Congress]] as well as the World Digital Library, the latter created by the [[UNESCO]] in order to distribute cultural and academic content,<ref name="Diario de Sevilla">{{cite news|last1=Diario de Sevilla|first1=Diario de Sevilla|title=La Unesco rescata la Sevilla de los Lumière|url=http://www.diariodesevilla.es/article/semanasanta2009/404279/la/unesco/rescata/la/sevilla/los/lumiere.html|accessdate=1 November 2016|work=Diario de Sevilla|agency=Joly Digita|issue=Semana Santa|publisher=Diario de Sevilla|date=10/03/2010}}</ref> distributed the video in a digital format via the Internet .<ref name="WDL" /><ref name="Library of Congress">{{cite web|last1=Library of Congress|first1=Library of Congress|title=Procession at Séville and bullfighting scenes|url=https://www.loc.gov/item/2006640141/|website=Library of Congress|publisher=Library of Congress|accessdate=1 November 2016}}</ref>
