{{Infobox stadium | name = RSN Stadium | nickname = | logo_image = | logo_caption = | image = | caption = | fullname = RSN Stadium | former_names = | location = [[Phnom Penh]], [[Cambodia]] | coordinates = | broke_ground = 2014 | built = | opened = 2015 | renovated = | expanded = | closed = | demolished = | owner = Rithy Samnang | operator = [[Phnom Penh Crown FC|Phnom Penh Crown]] | surface = | scoreboard = | estimated_cost = | suites = | architect = | project_manager = | structural engineer = | services engineer = | general_contractor = | main_contractors = | capacity = 5,000<ref name="PPP">{{cite news|title=Phnom Penh Crown to celebrate 5,000-seat stadium |url=http://www.phnompenhpost.com/sport/phnom-penh-crown-celebrate-5000-seat-stadium |publisher=Phnom Penh Post |date=3 June 2015 |accessdate=3 July 2015}}</ref> | record_attendance = | executive_suites = | dimensions = 105 x 68 m | acreage = | tenants = [[Phnom Penh Crown FC|Phnom Penh Crown]] }} '''RSN Stadium''' is a [[Soccer-specific stadium|football stadium]] in [[Phnom Penh]], [[Cambodia]], and the home of [[Cambodian League]] club [[Phnom Penh Crown FC|Phnom Penh Crown]].<ref name="PPP"/> The all-seater RSN Stadium is named after the club owner, Rithy Samnang. The stadium was opened with the RSN Youth Cup in June 2015 with a 4-team international tournament including Malaysia's Frenz United and Chonburi and Muangthong United from Thailand. All proceeds from the tournament were given to the Kantha Bopha Children’s Hospital.
