{{Infobox venue | name = Stade Arsène Wenger | nickname = | native_name = Stade Arsène Wenger | native_name_lang = French | fullname = Stade Arsène Wenger | former names = | logo_image = | logo_caption = | image = | image_size = | image_alt = | caption = | pushpin_map = | pushpin_mapsize = | pushpin_map_caption = | pushpin_label_position = | address = | location = [[Duppigheim]], [[Alsace]], France | coordinates = <!-- {{Coord|LAT|LON|type:landmark|display=inline,title}} --> | type = | genre = | broke_ground = | built = | opened = {{Start date|2016|05|23|df=y}} | renovated = | expanded = | closed = | demolished = | owner = | operator = USL Duppigheim | surface = | scoreboard = | production = | cost = | architect = | project_manager = | structural engineer = | services engineer = | general_contractor = | main_contractors = | seating_type = | capacity = 500 | suites = | record_attendance = | dimensions = | field_shape = | acreage = | volume = | tenants = | embedded = | website = <!-- {{URL|example.com}} --> | publictransit = }}
[[File:Arsene Wenger.JPG|thumb|150px|[[Arsène Wenger]], for whom the stadium is named]] '''Stade Arsène Wenger''' ''([[French language|French]]: Arsène Wenger Stadium)'', also erroneously called ''Stade de Arsène Wenger'' in international usage,<ref name=espn /> is an [[association football]] stadium in [[Duppigheim]], [[Alsace]], France. It was built in 2016 and it is the home ground of USL Duppigheim with a capacity of 500 seats. It is named after the former manager of the [[Premier League]] team [[Arsenal F.C.|Arsenal]], [[Arsène Wenger]] who grew up in nearby [[Duttlenheim]].<ref name=metro>{{cite web|url=http://metro.co.uk/2016/05/22/arsenal-boss-arsene-wenger-now-has-a-stadium-named-after-him-5898567/ |title=Arsenal news: 'Stade Arsene Wenger' – stadium named after Arsenal boss |publisher=Metro |date= |accessdate=2016-05-23}}</ref>
== History== USL Duppigheim initially played their home at Rue de Stade in Duppigheim, though Stade Arsène Wenger was built to replace it. The location that Stade Arsène Wenger built upon used to be a farmer's field mostly used for growing potatoes.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.lequipe.fr/Football/Actualites/Arsene-wenger-inaugure-un-stade-a-son-nom-en-alsace/680298 |title=Arsène Wenger inaugure un stade à son nom en Alsace |publisher=Lequipe.fr |language=French |date= |accessdate=2016-05-23}}</ref> In 2016, a new 500-seat stadium was built on the site of this field at a cost of €750,000 (£580,000).<ref name=bleu>{{cite web|url=https://www.francebleu.fr/infos/societe/arsene-wenger-donne-son-nom-au-stade-de-football-de-duppigheim-1463938330 |title=Arsène Wenger donne son nom au stade de football de Duppigheim |publisher=Francebleu.fr |language=French |date=1999-02-22 |accessdate=2016-05-23}}</ref> To commemorate his contribution to football, it was named after Arsenal manager Arsène Wenger.<ref>{{cite web|last=Whaling |first=James |url=https://www.mirror.co.uk/sport/football/news/arsene-wenger-travels-back-hometown-8028183 |title=Arsene Wenger travels back to hometown in Alsace to open new stadium named after him – Mirror Online |publisher=Mirror.co.uk |date= |accessdate=2016-05-23}}</ref> The stadium is located {{convert|3|km}} between Duppigheim and Duttlenheim but is considered to be administratively in Duppigheim. Duppigheim residents jokingly stated "who will tell the guys in Duttlenheim?" upon the news that the stadium named after Wenger would be in Duppigheim.<ref>{{cite web|author=A Duppigheim, Floréal Hernandez |url=http://www.20minutes.fr/strasbourg/1849835-20160522-football-arsene-wenger-inaugure-premier-stade-nom-3-km-village-natal |title=Arsène Wenger inaugure le premier stade à son nom à 3 km de son village natal |language=French |publisher=20minutes.fr |date= |accessdate=2016-05-23}}</ref>
The stadium was opened by Wenger in May 2016 in front of 600 people. During the ceremony, he stated that he recalled: "When I was little, this stadium was a field of potatoes. Now it looks like [[Wembley Stadium|Wembley]]."<ref name=bleu /> Wenger also stated that "It’s an honour. I am a little surprised."<ref>{{cite web|author=Vaishali Bhardwaj |url=https://www.standard.co.uk/sport/football/arsenal-manager-inaugurates-stade-arsene-wenger-in-french-region-where-he-grew-up-a3254151.html |title=Stade Arsene Wenger: Arsenal manager opens venue in French region where he grew up |publisher=Evening Standard |date= |accessdate=2016-05-23}}</ref> The USL Duppigheim chairman Peter Troesch stated that it was an "easy choice" and proclaimed that "He [Wenger] deserves to have one in every village in Alsace and France."<ref name=espn>{{cite web|url=http://www.espnfc.com/arsenal/story/2878110/arsenal-boss-arsene-wenger-opens-stadium-named-after-him-in-france |title=Arsenal boss Arsene Wenger opens stadium named after him in France |publisher=ESPN |date= |accessdate=2016-05-23}}</ref>
